**Steps to Reproduce**:

Compile the following code
```cs
class Test
{
  #nullable disable
  public string oblivious;
  #nullable enable
  public string notnullable = "";
  public string? nullable = null;
  
  void M()
  {
    var cOfOblivious = GetC(ref oblivious); // C<string:[Oblivious]> doesn't warn anywhere
    cOfOblivious.Prop.ToString(); // C<string?> would warn there
    cOfOblivious.Prop = null;     // C<string!> would warn there
    
    var cOfNotNullable = GetC(ref notnullable);
    cOfNotNullable.Prop.ToString();
    cOfNotNullable.Prop = null;   // C<string>! warns
      
    var cOfNullable = GetC(ref nullable);
    cOfNullable.Prop.ToString();  // C<string?> warns
    cOfNullable.Prop = null;
  }
    
  C<T> GetC<T>(ref T t) => new C<T>(t);
}
public class C<T>
{
  public T Prop { get; set; }
  public C(T t) => Prop = t;
}
```

**Expected Behavior**:
Oblivious annotation isn't inferred in `#nullable` context so `cOfOblivious` is either `C<string?>` or `C<string>`

**Actual Behavior**:
`cOfOblivious` has oblivious annotation for its type argument and doesn't warn neither for dereferences of its property nor on null assignments to it

This PR allows code to use `emscripten_set_main_loop` (https://emscripten.org/docs/api_reference/emscripten.h.html#browser-execution-environment).
This is possible with the .net 5 compiler and the use of e.g.
```
        [DllImport("*")]
        internal static extern unsafe void emscripten_set_main_loop(delegate*<void> f,  int fps, int simulate_infinite_loop);

        [UnmanagedCallersOnly(EntryPoint = "MainLoop", CallingConvention = CallingConvention.Cdecl)]
        static void MainLoop()
        {
            Console.WriteLine("Main loop");
        }
```
and
```
        emscripten_set_main_loop(&MainLoop, 0, 0);
```

It adds handling for `TypeFlags.FunctionPointer` and adds a call to `RhpReversePInvokeReturn2` when the main function exits as emscripten will subsequently make calls into the main loop function and the thread state needs to go back to preemptive.

This code will print Hello World until all eternity on CoreCLR but exit immediately and print nothing on CoreRT.

```csharp
using System;
using System.Threading;

class Program
{
    static void Main(string[] args)
    {
        var t = new Thread(Meh);
        t.IsBackground = false;
        t.Start();
    }

    private static void Meh(object obj)
    {
        while (true)
        {
            Thread.Sleep(10);
            Console.WriteLine("Hello World!");
        }
    }
}
```

